# Botho consensus spec — project brief

The normative specification for Botho's consensus and wire format. It lives in
the same repository as its Rust implementation and must stay truthful to it:
every constant, struct layout, formula, and block-validity predicate either
matches the implementation, or is explicitly marked target-state with the gap
tracked.

## What this spec governs (and what it defers)

- **Normative**: the constants, message/struct layouts, formulas, and validity
  predicates an implementer must satisfy to be conformant.
- **Marked target-state**: where the live implementation and the intended
  design diverge (e.g. a feature specified but not yet shipped), the divergence
  is recorded in the `## Implementation status` register (a live/target/status/
  tracking row per component), not silently canonized to either side.
  `spec-audit` suppresses a registered gap and flags an unregistered one.

## Reference material

- `refs/` — ADRs, design notes, and diagram sources (mermaid state machines,
  message flows).
- The `code_ref` implementation is the consistency oracle: `spec-audit` reads
  it to flag any normative claim that appears to contradict the implementation
  — surfacing the ambiguous fix direction to the operator rather than presuming
  the code is authoritative (the near-miss this class exists to prevent).

## Adopting the existing whitepaper

This spec predates anvil adoption — it is already a multi-file LaTeX tree. See
`anvil/skills/spec/SKILL.md` §"Adopting an existing spec" for the placement
procedure: put the existing `<slug>.tex` + `sections/*.tex` into
`botho-consensus-spec/botho-consensus-spec.1/`, register the thread here, and
start the lifecycle at `spec-review` / `spec-audit`.
